# Core Labs — IP boundary rules

This repository is the **shared platform technology layer**. It serves multiple independent product companies. Every piece of code here must be reusable across all of them.

## What belongs here

- Generic packages reusable by any product company
- App and service templates with no product-specific logic
- Engineering Standard rules (v3.1)
- Governance, IP, and license documents
- Project generator and wizard scripts
- CI/CD workflow templates

## What NEVER belongs here

Do not add any of the following:

- `Vouus`, `ERP`, `Frappe`, `ERPNext`, `erp-labs`, `vouus` as product identifiers
- Customer-specific business rules or data models
- ERP compliance workflows (leave management, payroll, expense policies)
- Frappe session management or ERPNext site provisioning logic
- Product-specific pricing strategies (erp-labs plan tiers, Vouus SKUs)
- Hardcoded domains, API endpoints, or credentials
- Code that only makes sense for one specific product

## Every new package must include

- `README.md` — purpose, public API, usage example
- `SOURCE.md` — origin path, extraction date, removed items, ownership declaration
- `LICENSE.md` — reference to Core Labs Internal Commercial License (CLICL v1.0)
- `src/index.ts` — public API barrel only (no internal implementation details exported)

## Every code movement must be logged

Before merging code from a product repository into Core Labs:

1. Remove all product-specific identifiers.
2. Add `SOURCE.md` to the new package.
3. Add an entry to `MIGRATION_LOG.md` at the repo root.
4. Update `SOURCE_CODE_INVENTORY.md`.

## Adapters belong in product repositories

Code that connects a Core Labs package to a product-specific system is an **adapter** and belongs in the product repository, not here.

Example: `core-auth-to-frappe.ts` belongs in `erp-labs`, not in `@core-labs/auth-kit`.

## Environment variable naming

Core Labs packages use neutral env var prefixes. Never hardcode product-specific prefixes:

| Forbidden | Use instead |
|---|---|
| `VOUUS_*` | `APP_*` or `SERVICE_*` |
| `ERP_*` | `TENANT_*` or `SERVICE_*` |
| `FRAPPE_*` | `ERP_BACKEND_*` (in adapter code, not here) |

## Cloudflare resource naming

Follow `10-naming-standard.mdc` Cloudflare resource pattern. Never use:
- Public brand names in Worker/Pages/D1/KV slugs
- Hostnames as resource identifiers
- Customer-facing product names as infrastructure identifiers
